s, a prime function of the modern state is ensuring access to cheap, reliable sources to power and grow the economy. Historically, energy is more of a zero-sum resource than capital, markets, labor, or technology, and thus is a greater source of geopolitical tension and violence. Energy politics, and by extension international politics is, moreover, shaped by domestic corporate elites, especially those within the United States.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aEnergy developmentxPolitical aspectsxHistory. 0aEnergy developmentxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aEnergy policyxHistory. 0aEnergy policyzUnited StatesxHistory. 4aHistory : American History. 4aHistory : World History. 4aPolitics and Law : International Relations. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Economy. 4aPublic Policy : Energy Policy. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2018z978311149142440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781438469829?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438469829423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438469829/original  a978-3-11-149142-4  SUNY Press eBook Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles